{{Cite thesis\n  | last = House\n  | first = Albert V.\n  | title = The Political Career of Samuel Jackson Randall\n  | type = Ph.D.\n  | url = http://minds.wisconsin.edu/handle/1793/406\n  | publisher = University of Wisconsin\n  | date = 1934\n  | oclc = 51818085\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n\n'''Website'''\n* {{cite web\n |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3O.HTM\n |title=Code of Canon Law\n |date=1983\n |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana\n |access-date=February 26, 2017\n |ref={{sfnRef|Code of Canon Law}}\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402021547/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P3O.HTM\n |archivedate=2 April 2007\n |df=dmy-all\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box |\n   before=[[Michael Francis Egan]] |\n  title=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|Bishop of Philadelphia]] |\n  years=1819\u20131842 |\n  after=[[Francis Kenrick]]\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conwell, Henry}}\n[[Category:1740s births]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish clergy]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish clergy]]\n[[Category:People from County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Irish College, Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:Irish emigrants to the United States (before 1923)]]\n[[Category:19th-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Cathedral Basilica of Saints Peter and Paul, Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "184.170.166.199", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Conwell"}
{"title_page": "Number Our Days", "text_new": "{{short description|1976 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Number Our Days\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Lynne Littman]]\n| producer       = Loring d'Usseau<br>Lynne Littman<br>[[Barbara Myerhoff]]\n| writer         = Lynne Littman<br>[[Barbara Myerhoff]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Harry Asimow\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Neil Reichline\n| editing        = [[Lewis Teague]]\n| studio         = [[KCET]]\n| distributor    = [[Direct Cinema Limited]]\n| released       = {{film date|1976}}\n| runtime        = 28 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English \n}}\n\n'''''Number Our Days''''' is a 1976 American [[short film|short]] [[documentary film]] about a community of elderly [[Jews]] living in [[Venice, California]]. Directed by [[Lynne Littman]], it won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] at the [[49th Academy Awards]], held in 1977, for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Documentary Short Subject]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300412/Number-Our-Days/details |title=New York Times: Number Our Days |accessdate=May 27, 2008 |work=NY Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520034406/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300412/Number-Our-Days/details |archive-date=May 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Oscars1977\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1977 |title=The 49th Academy Awards (1977) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=June 12, 2019|work=oscars.org}}</ref> The [[Academy Film Archive]] preserved ''Number Our Days'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=number+our+days&filmmaker=&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Harry Asimow as Himself (archive footage)\n* [[Barbara Myerhoff]] as Herself\n* [[Lynne Littman]] as Herself (voice) (uncredited)\n* During the film a band is shown. The band leader is Eddie Gurnick who was a musician in Los Angeles.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.directcinema.com/category/8/235 ''Number Our Days''] at [[Direct Cinema Limited]]\n*{{IMDb title|id=0074987|title=Number Our Days}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Documentary Short |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:1970s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Short documentary films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in California]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about old age]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Venice, California]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Jews and Judaism in the United States]]\n{{reli-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1976 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Number Our Days\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Lynne Littman]]\n| producer       = Loring d'Usseau<br>Lynne Littman<br>[[Barbara Myerhoff]]\n| writer         = Lynne Littman<br>[[Barbara Myerhoff]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = Harry Asimow\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Neil Reichline\n| editing        = [[Lewis Teague]]\n| studio         = [[KCET]]\n| distributor    = [[Direct Cinema Limited]]\n| released       = {{film date|1976}}\n| runtime        = 28 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = English \n}}\n\n'''''Number Our Days''''' is a 1976 American [[short film|short]] [[documentary film]] about a community of elderly [[Jews]] living in [[Venice, California]]. Directed by [[Lynne Littman]], it won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] at the [[49th Academy Awards]], held in 1977, for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)|Documentary Short Subject]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300412/Number-Our-Days/details |title=New York Times: Number Our Days |accessdate=May 27, 2008 |work=NY Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520034406/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300412/Number-Our-Days/details |archive-date=May 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Oscars1977\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1977 |title=The 49th Academy Awards (1977) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=June 12, 2019|work=oscars.org}}</ref> The [[Academy Film Archive]] preserved ''Number Our Days'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=number+our+days&filmmaker=&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Harry Asimow as Himself (archive footage)\n* [[Barbara Myerhoff]] as Herself\n* [[Lynne Littman]] as Herself (voice) (uncredited)\n* During the film a band is shown. The band leader is Eddie Gurnick who was a musician in Los Angeles.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.directcinema.com/category/8/235 ''Number Our Days''] at [[Direct Cinema Limited]]\n*{{IMDb title|id=0074987|title=Number Our Days}}\n\n{{Academy Award Best Documentary Short |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:1970s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Short documentary films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Best Documentary Short Subject Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in California]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about old age]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Venice, California]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Jews and Judaism in the United States]]\n{{reli-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "