{"title_page": "Iwan Fals", "text_new": "{{short description|Indonesian singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Iwan Fals\n| image            = Iwan Fals, 2015.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Iwan Fals during Performance in 2015\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Virgiawan Listanto\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1961|09|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]\n| origin           = [[Jakarta]]\n| genre            = [[folk music]], [[country music|country]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| associated_acts  = Kantata Takwa, Swami\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| url              = http://www.iwanfals.co.id/\n}}\n\n'''Iwan Fals''' (born '''Virgiawan Listanto'''; 3 September 1961 in [[Jakarta]]) is an [[Indonesia]]n [[Singing|singer]]\u2013[[songwriter]]. In 2002, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named him as a Great Asian Hero. His musical style has been said to be pop, rock, country, and folk pop and his lyrics tell a lot of dark times from the 1970s to 1980s in the political field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gridoto.com/read/221004246/ini-beberapa-alasan-iwan-fals-jadi-brand-ambassador-mitsubishi-fuso|title=Ini Beberapa Alasan Iwan Fals Jadi Brand Ambassador Mitsubishi FUSO - GridOto.com|last=GridOto.com|website=www.gridoto.com|language=id|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nIwan was born Virgiawan Listanto in Jakarta, on 3 September 1961 to Harsoyo, a soldier,<ref name=\"ginting286\"/> and Lies Suudijah. He studied at SMP Negeri 5 Bandung and SMAK BPK Bandung. He continued his studies at Sekolah Tinggi Publisistik and then Institut Kesenian Jakarta. At the age of thirteen, he appeared as a street musician in small wedding ceremonies and other social events.<ref>{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|pp=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhile he was 18, Iwan Fals, Toto Gunarto, Helmi, Bambang Bule and Kakek Jagonk formed a group named Amburadul. The group released the album 'Perjalanan' in 1979, which was not successful, but was re-released with the added track '3 Bulan' as '3 Bulan' (1980) in 1980. The group disbanded and played no further role in Iwan Fals' career.\n\nAs part of his early career, Iwan Fals also recorded some comedy albums, after winning a comedy country singing contest. He sang of comic situations and themes, and his first release was on 'Canda Dalam Nada' (the A-side featured five songs by Iwan: Generasi Frustrasi, Dongeng Tidur, Imitasi, Kisah Sepeda Motorku (aka. Kopral), and Joni Kesiangan while the B-side consisted of songs by Tom Slepe and Pusaka Jaya). The songs Dongeng Tidur, Joni Kesiangan and Kisah Sepeda Motorku were released, with one new song, Ambulance Zig Zag, on the Iwan Fals mini-album Canda Dalam Nada, while Generasi Frustrasi and Imitasi were also included on the 'Yang Muda Yang Bercanda II' multiartist comedy compilation.\n\nDuring this time, Iwan supported himself by busking.\n\n1981 saw Iwan Fals' breakthrough, when he signed to Musica Studio to record his first solo album, ''[[Sarjana Muda]]''. This album shows Iwan Fals' signature country music style, with the protest song \"Guru Oemar Bakrie\", which talks of how a teacher is poorly paid but still responsible for educating future well-paid and successful people. 'Guru Oemar Bakrie' became very well known and popular in Indonesia, and helped established Iwan's name. The album also contains several ballads. It benefited from considerable investment by Musica Studio, who used high-quality musicians and producer for the album.\n\n1982's Opini, also on Musica Studio, cemented Iwan's reputation as a protest singer, but also as a balladeer. 'Galang Rambu Anarki', for his newborn son, combined both elements, commenting on both the happy event of the birth of his first child, but also commenting on rising prices, saying that perhaps his child would be malnourished if they could not afford to buy milk.\n\n1983 saw the release of ''Sumbang'', while 1984's album releases were ''Barang Antik'' and ''Sugali''.\n\nIn April 1984, Iwan was arrested and questioned for two weeks after performing the songs 'Demokrasi Nasi' and ''Mbak Tini'', both songs never recorded on album, in [[Pekanbaru]]. The song Mbak Tini was about a prostitute with a road-side coffee shop, married to 'Soeharyo' ([[Suharto]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/02/08/182515/1563366/1093/iwan-fals-berterimakasih-kepada-orde-baru-dan-mengagumi-soeharto |title=Iwan Fals Berterimakasih Kepada Orde Baru dan Mengagumi Soeharto |accessdate=2012-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714153523/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/02/08/182515/1563366/1093/iwan-fals-berterimakasih-kepada-orde-baru-dan-mengagumi-soeharto |archivedate=2012-07-14 |df= }}</ref> The events were retold on the song '14-4-84' on 1986's Ethiopia.\n\nIwan Fals continued to release albums throughout the 1980s, while in 1989 he formed the group ''Swami'', which released two albums ''Swami I'' in 1989, and ''Swami II'' in 1991. A similar grouping was ''Kantata Takwa'', which contained several Swami personnel. The musical style was \"rebana rock\", a blend of [[Jimi Hendrix]] and [[Rick Wakeman]], to a Betawi rebana.<ref>{{harvnb|Sen|Hill|2000|p=182}}</ref> The album ''Kantata Takwa'' was released in 1990, featuring songs such as \"Bento\" and \"Bongkar\" (\"Rip It Down\"), two of several songs which they sang during a demonstration by college students.<ref name=\"aning96\">{{harvnb|Aning S.|2006|p=96}}</ref>\n\nUp to the release ''Orang Gila'' in 1994, Iwan had released approximately two new albums per year for 15 years. Since 1994, he has greatly reduced his release schedule, putting out only two singles in 1995, and one in 1996, while in 1998 Kantata Samsara, the second and final album by Kantata Takwa, was released.\n\nTo make up for the lack of new content, a number of Iwan Fals compilations were released in the 1990s and 2000s, including ''Best Of The Best'', ''Akustik'' (3 volumes), and ''Salam Reformasi'' (\"Greetings Reformation\"), which sold more than 50,000 copies.<ref>{{cite journal |date=October 24, 1998 |title=Rising R&B, Duetting Dangdut, Singing Spirituals |journal=Billboard |volume=110 |page=APQ-2 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |issn=0006-2510 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQoEAAAAMBAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Iwan Fals released his first new solo album since 1994, ''Suara Hati''.<ref name=\"ubaedy4\">{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|p=4}}</ref> In 2003 the album 'In Collaboration With' was released consisting of performances with other Indonesia artists. ''Manusia Setengah Dewa'', in 2004, was a solo album.\n\nIn 2005, he released ''Iwan Fals In Love'', essentially a compilation of existing Iwan Fals romantic recordings, but with the new song \"Ijinkan Aku Menyayangimu\" (\"Let Me Love You\") as the main single, and five re-recordings of old songs.<ref name=\"klc\"/> Two songs, in collaboration with Indra Lesmana, ''Haruskah Pergi'', and ''Selancar'', were released as digital download in 2006.\n\nIn 2007, ''50:50'' was released by Musica Studios. The album's themes were romance and social criticism. One single of the album, \"Pulanglah\" (\"Go Home\"), tells about the death of [[Munir Said Thalib|Munir]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|pp=289\u2013291}}</ref> Six singles were written by himself and other six singles were written by his fellow musicians.<ref name=\"klc\"/> Two songs were released in 2009 as ''Untukmu Terkasih''.\n\nIn 2010, he released ''Keseimbangan'', and in 2011 he released a new album titled \"Tergila-gila\" with 4 new songs inside.\n\n=== OI ===\nHe has a large fan club which is called ''OI'' (stylised as lowercase ''oi)'', he stated \"''Oi'' is not [actually] Orang Indonesia, so there are many friends (fans) whose faces I recognise, but [I] can't remember their names.\" He started calling his fans who often come to his house to listen his free acoustic live performance with \"Oi\" which literally means \"Hey\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Taufik Rahaji|title=Iwan Fals Akhirnya Bicara - Kick Andy - FULL|date=2013-06-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7aTyziIi7Dk|accessdate=2018-05-09}}</ref> Thus, the fans derived ''OI'' as the name of the fan club and made it as an abbreviation from ''Orang Indonesia'' (''Indonesian People'') as the acronym must contain a meaning. The idea of naming ''Orang Indonesia'' came from Iwan Fals' foundation, ''Yayasan Orang Indonesia'' (''Indonesian People Foundation''). OI is now led by his wife and running under the management of ''PT. Tiga Rambu'' (limited liability company).<ref>{{Citation|last=Netmediatama|title=Sarah Sechan - Tahun Baruan bareng Iwan Fals|date=2014-01-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KharSea4QO8|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOi was made as the reflection of his passed-away son, and to become the father of his fans.\n\n==Lyrical themes==\nIwan Fals has been compared with Bob Dylan, who was one of his key influences, both on his early style, which made heavy use of the [[harmonica]], and on his lyrics, which have frequently been in the [[protest song]] genre.\n\nFor instance, \"Kamu Sudah Gila\" (\"You've Gone Crazy\") and \"Apa Kamu Sudah Jadi Tuhan?\" (\"Have You Become God?\") criticised the [[New Order (Indonesia)|New Order regime]].\n\nOther songs are more observational, but still could be seen as political. For instance, his song Galang Rambu Anarki, written for his newborn son, talks of being too poor to raise his son, while \"Kembang Pete\" (\"Stinkbean Flower\") tells the story of the underestimated poor.<ref name=\"ginting286\">{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|p=286}}</ref> \"Aku Bosan\" (\"I'm Bored\") is about a child protesting to his parents because they left him alone at home. While \"Hura-Hura Huru-Hara\" (\"Fake Riot\") compares moneylender to blood-sucking vampires.<ref>{{harvnb|Emmerson|1999|p=286}}</ref>\n\nThe 1988 song (and album) '1910', which could be interpreted as referring to the year 1910, was actually a reference to the date 19 October, the date, in 1987, of the [[Bintaro train crash]], a disaster the song documents in observational style. \"Celoteh Camar Tolol dan Cemar\", on 1983's Sumbang, documented the sinking of the ''Tampomas II'' ship in [[Masalembu Islands|Masalembu]].\n\nAside from his observational protest songs, Iwan Fals is known for his love songs, which include \"Yang Terlupakan\" (\"The Forgotten\"), \"Mata Indah Bola Pingpong\" (\"Beautiful Pingpong Ball Eyes\"), \"Antara Kau, Aku, dan Bekas Pacarmu\" (\"Among You, Me, and Your ex-lover\"), and \"Pesawat Tempurku\" (\"My Jet Fighter\").\n\nAlthough a songwriter, Iwan Fals' status as one of Indonesia's leading rock/pop performers has led to his recording material from numerous other songwriters. Some of his most notable hits written by others include Barang Antik (\"Antique\"), \"Kemesraan\" (\"Intimacy\"), \"Kumenanti Seorang Kekasih\" (\"I'm Waiting for a Lover\"), \"Aku Bukan Pilihan\" (\"I'm Not an Option\") and \"Ijinkan Aku Menyayangimu\" (\"Let Me Love You\").<ref>{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|p=289}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 1 January 1982, Fals' first son, Galang Rambu Anarki was born. One of Fals' best-known songs, Galang Rambu Anarki, was written for his son's birth and released on 1982's Opini  (Opinion) album.  Galang was following in his father's footsteps playing in a band from a young age as a guitarist and folk musician, but he died aged only 15, on 25 April 1997 of either a [[morphine]] overdose or asthma. 'Galang Rambu Anarki' translates to \"support the sign of anarchy\" in English.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetmole.org/daily/indonesians-in-focus-iwan-fals.html|title=Indonesians in Focus: Iwan Fals|work=planetmole.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://suaramerdeka.com/v1/index.php/read/cetak/2010/04/22/106730/Dapat-Julukan-Kiai-dari-Santri-Rembang|title=SUARA MERDEKA CETAK - Dapat Julukan Kiai dari Santri Rembang|author=Suara Merdeka CyberNews|work=suaramerdeka.com|access-date=2012-02-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425003809/http://suaramerdeka.com/v1/index.php/read/cetak/2010/04/22/106730/Dapat-Julukan-Kiai-dari-Santri-Rembang|archive-date=2010-04-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Fals' first daughter Annisa Cikal Rambu Basae was born.<ref name=\"ubaedy3\">{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|p=3}}</ref> His third child is Rayya Rambu Robbani.<ref name=\"klc\">{{cite web |url=http://selebriti.kapanlagi.com/indonesia/i/iwan_fals/ |title=Iwan Fals |work=KapanLagi.com |accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref> He and Rosanna, his wife live in [[Cibubur]], [[West Java]].<ref name=\"aning96\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n* Perjalanan (as part of Amburadul group) (1979)\n* Canda Dalam Nada (1979) - comedy album, Iwan has the A-side only\n* Canda Dalam Ronda (1980) - comedy mini-album of four tracks, contains one new track 'Ambulance Zig Zag'\n* 3 Bulan (consists of Perjalanan plus the new track ''3 Bulan'') (1980)\n* [[Sarjana Muda]] (1981) - Musica debut\n* [[Opini]] (1982)\n* [[Sumbang]] (1983)\n* [[Barang Antik]] (1984)\n* [[Sugali (Iwan Fals album)|Sugali]] (1984)\n* [[Kelompok Penyanyi Jalanan]] (KPJ) - as part of KPJ, or Street Singers Group, Iwan Fals sings on 3 songs (1985)\n* [[Sore Tugu Pancoran]] (1985)\n* [[Aku Sayang Kamu]] (1986)\n* [[Ethiopia (Iwan Fals album)|Ethiopia]] (1986)\n* [[Lancar]] (1987)\n* [[Wakil Rakyat]] (1987)\n* 1910 (1988)\n* [[Kemesraan]] (1988) - single, with Betharia Sonata, [[Chrisye]], Rafika Duri, Itang, [[Jamal Mirdad]], Etrie, Nani\n* [[Mata Dewa]] (1989)\n* [[Swami I]] (as part of the group Swami) (1989)\n* [[Kantata Takwa]] (as part of the group Kantata) (1990)\n* [[Cikal]] (1991)\n* [[Swami II]] (as part of the group Swami)  (1991)\n* [[Belum Ada Judul]] (1992)\n* [[Hijau]] (1992)\n* [[Dalbo (Iwan Fals album)|Dalbo]] (1993)\n* [[Anak Wayang]] (1994)\n* [[Orang Gila]] (1994)\n* [[Kantata Samsara]] (as part of the group Kantata) (1998)\n* [[Suara Hati]] (2002)\n* [[In Collaboration with]] (2003)\n* [[Manusia Setengah Dewa]] (2004)\n* [[In Love (Iwan Fals album)|In Love]] (2005) (contains only one new song, and four re-recordings)\n* [[50:50]] (2007)\n* [[Untukmu Terkasih]] (2009) - [[Mini-album]] - two songs only\n* [[Keseimbangan]] (2010)\n* [[Tergila-gila]] (2011)\n* Raya (2013)\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2002, he was named as Great Asian Hero by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"ubaedy4\"/> In 2011, he received \"Satyalancana\", the highest government awards from [[Jero Wacik]], Culture and Tourism Minister of Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/03/24/pop-singer-iwan-fals-receives-highest-government-award-dedication.html |title=Pop singer Iwan Fals receives highest government award for dedication |date=24 March 2011 |newspaper=The Jakarta Post |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013081501/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/03/24/pop-singer-iwan-fals-receives-highest-government-award-dedication.html |archivedate=13 October 2011 |df= }}</ref> \n\nRolling Stone Indonesia listed Swami's song Bongkar as the best Indonesian song of all time and Bento on the fifth position, Kantata Takwa's Kesaksian on 81st position, and Iwan Fals' solo Guru Oemar Bakrie, Yang Terlupakan, Surat Buat Wakil Rakyat, Pesawat Tempur, Galang Rambu Anarki, and Sarjana Muda on 5th, 42nd, 51st, 56th, 65th, and 97th, respectively, making him the second musician with the most representative on the chart after [[Koes Plus]] with the margin of one.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |title=100 Tokoh Yang Mengubah Indonesia |last=Aning S. |first=Floriberta |year=2006 |publisher=Narasi |location=Yogyakarta |isbn=9789797564759 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLrkTdG_9xEC |edition=Revised |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Indonesia Beyond Suharto: Polity, Economy, Society, Transition |last=Emmerson |first=Donald K. |year=1999 |publisher=M. E. Sharpe |location=Armonk, N.Y. |isbn=9781563248900 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQjzLRYXJZQC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Musisiku |last=Ginting |first=Asrat  |year=2009 |publisher=Republika |location=Jakarta |isbn=9789791102520 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ig3oH5TGv4oC |ref=harv|display-authors=etal}}\n* {{cite book |title=Media, Culture and Politics in Indonesia |last=Sen |first=Krishna |last2=Hill |first2=David T. |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=South Melbourne, Vict. |isbn=9780195537031 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xMhWm38KQcsC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Refleksi Kehidupan: Kisah dan Kajian Hidup Orang-Orang Ternama |last=Ubaedy |first=A. N. |first2=Imam |last2=Ratrioso |year=2005 |publisher=Elex Media Komputindo |location=Jakarta |isbn=9789792077254 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o85mshB9IK8C |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fals, Iwan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Indonesian country singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Jakarta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indonesian singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Iwan Fals\n| image            = Iwan Fals, 2015.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Iwan Fals during Performance in 2015\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Virgiawan Listanto\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1961|09|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]\n| origin           = [[Jakarta]]\n| genre            = [[folk music]], [[country music|country]], [[pop music|pop]]\n| associated_acts  = Kantata Takwa, Swami\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| url              = http://www.iwanfals.co.id/\n}}\n\n'''Iwan Fals''' (born '''Virgiawan Listanto'''; 3 September 1961 in [[Jakarta]]) is an [[Indonesia]]n [[Singing|singer]]\u2013[[songwriter]]. In 2002, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine named him as a Great Asian Hero.\n\n==Early life==\nIwan was born Virgiawan Listanto in Jakarta, on 3 September 1961 to Harsoyo, a soldier,<ref name=\"ginting286\"/> and Lies Suudijah. He studied at SMP Negeri 5 Bandung and SMAK BPK Bandung. He continued his studies at Sekolah Tinggi Publisistik and then Institut Kesenian Jakarta. At the age of thirteen, he appeared as a street musician in small wedding ceremonies and other social events.<ref>{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|pp=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhile he was 18, Iwan Fals, Toto Gunarto, Helmi, Bambang Bule and Kakek Jagonk formed a group named Amburadul. The group released the album 'Perjalanan' in 1979, which was not successful, but was re-released with the added track '3 Bulan' as '3 Bulan' (1980) in 1980. The group disbanded and played no further role in Iwan Fals' career.\n\nAs part of his early career, Iwan Fals also recorded some comedy albums, after winning a comedy country singing contest. He sang of comic situations and themes, and his first release was on 'Canda Dalam Nada' (the A-side featured five songs by Iwan: Generasi Frustrasi, Dongeng Tidur, Imitasi, Kisah Sepeda Motorku (aka. Kopral), and Joni Kesiangan while the B-side consisted of songs by Tom Slepe and Pusaka Jaya). The songs Dongeng Tidur, Joni Kesiangan and Kisah Sepeda Motorku were released, with one new song, Ambulance Zig Zag, on the Iwan Fals mini-album Canda Dalam Nada, while Generasi Frustrasi and Imitasi were also included on the 'Yang Muda Yang Bercanda II' multiartist comedy compilation.\n\nDuring this time, Iwan supported himself by busking.\n\n1981 saw Iwan Fals' breakthrough, when he signed to Musica Studio to record his first solo album, ''[[Sarjana Muda]]''. This album shows Iwan Fals' signature country music style, with the protest song \"Guru Oemar Bakrie\", which talks of how a teacher is poorly paid but still responsible for educating future well-paid and successful people. 'Guru Oemar Bakrie' became very well known and popular in Indonesia, and helped established Iwan's name. The album also contains several ballads. It benefited from considerable investment by Musica Studio, who used high-quality musicians and producer for the album.\n\n1982's Opini, also on Musica Studio, cemented Iwan's reputation as a protest singer, but also as a balladeer. 'Galang Rambu Anarki', for his newborn son, combined both elements, commenting on both the happy event of the birth of his first child, but also commenting on rising prices, saying that perhaps his child would be malnourished if they could not afford to buy milk.\n\n1983 saw the release of ''Sumbang'', while 1984's album releases were ''Barang Antik'' and ''Sugali''.\n\nIn April 1984, Iwan was arrested and questioned for two weeks after performing the songs 'Demokrasi Nasi' and ''Mbak Tini'', both songs never recorded on album, in [[Pekanbaru]]. The song Mbak Tini was about a prostitute with a road-side coffee shop, married to 'Soeharyo' ([[Suharto]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/02/08/182515/1563366/1093/iwan-fals-berterimakasih-kepada-orde-baru-dan-mengagumi-soeharto |title=Iwan Fals Berterimakasih Kepada Orde Baru dan Mengagumi Soeharto |accessdate=2012-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714153523/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/02/08/182515/1563366/1093/iwan-fals-berterimakasih-kepada-orde-baru-dan-mengagumi-soeharto |archivedate=2012-07-14 |df= }}</ref> The events were retold on the song '14-4-84' on 1986's Ethiopia.\n\nIwan Fals continued to release albums throughout the 1980s, while in 1989 he formed the group ''Swami'', which released two albums ''Swami I'' in 1989, and ''Swami II'' in 1991. A similar grouping was ''Kantata Takwa'', which contained several Swami personnel. The musical style was \"rebana rock\", a blend of [[Jimi Hendrix]] and [[Rick Wakeman]], to a Betawi rebana.<ref>{{harvnb|Sen|Hill|2000|p=182}}</ref> The album ''Kantata Takwa'' was released in 1990, featuring songs such as \"Bento\" and \"Bongkar\" (\"Rip It Down\"), two of several songs which they sang during a demonstration by college students.<ref name=\"aning96\">{{harvnb|Aning S.|2006|p=96}}</ref>\n\nUp to the release ''Orang Gila'' in 1994, Iwan had released approximately two new albums per year for 15 years. Since 1994, he has greatly reduced his release schedule, putting out only two singles in 1995, and one in 1996, while in 1998 Kantata Samsara, the second and final album by Kantata Takwa, was released.\n\nTo make up for the lack of new content, a number of Iwan Fals compilations were released in the 1990s and 2000s, including ''Best Of The Best'', ''Akustik'' (3 volumes), and ''Salam Reformasi'' (\"Greetings Reformation\"), which sold more than 50,000 copies.<ref>{{cite journal |date=October 24, 1998 |title=Rising R&B, Duetting Dangdut, Singing Spirituals |journal=Billboard |volume=110 |page=APQ-2 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |issn=0006-2510 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQoEAAAAMBAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Iwan Fals released his first new solo album since 1994, ''Suara Hati''.<ref name=\"ubaedy4\">{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|p=4}}</ref> In 2003 the album 'In Collaboration With' was released consisting of performances with other Indonesia artists. ''Manusia Setengah Dewa'', in 2004, was a solo album.\n\nIn 2005, he released ''Iwan Fals In Love'', essentially a compilation of existing Iwan Fals romantic recordings, but with the new song \"Ijinkan Aku Menyayangimu\" (\"Let Me Love You\") as the main single, and five re-recordings of old songs.<ref name=\"klc\"/> Two songs, in collaboration with Indra Lesmana, ''Haruskah Pergi'', and ''Selancar'', were released as digital download in 2006.\n\nIn 2007, ''50:50'' was released by Musica Studios. The album's themes were romance and social criticism. One single of the album, \"Pulanglah\" (\"Go Home\"), tells about the death of [[Munir Said Thalib|Munir]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|pp=289\u2013291}}</ref> Six singles were written by himself and other six singles were written by his fellow musicians.<ref name=\"klc\"/> Two songs were released in 2009 as ''Untukmu Terkasih''.\n\nIn 2010, he released ''Keseimbangan'', and in 2011 he released a new album titled \"Tergila-gila\" with 4 new songs inside.\n\n=== OI ===\nHe has a large fan club which is called ''OI'' (stylised as lowercase ''oi)'', he stated \"''Oi'' is not [actually] Orang Indonesia, so there are many friends (fans) whose faces I recognise, but [I] can't remember their names.\" He started calling his fans who often come to his house to listen his free acoustic live performance with \"Oi\" which literally means \"Hey\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Taufik Rahaji|title=Iwan Fals Akhirnya Bicara - Kick Andy - FULL|date=2013-06-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7aTyziIi7Dk|accessdate=2018-05-09}}</ref> Thus, the fans derived ''OI'' as the name of the fan club and made it as an abbreviation from ''Orang Indonesia'' (''Indonesian People'') as the acronym must contain a meaning. The idea of naming ''Orang Indonesia'' came from Iwan Fals' foundation, ''Yayasan Orang Indonesia'' (''Indonesian People Foundation''). OI is now led by his wife and running under the management of ''PT. Tiga Rambu'' (limited liability company).<ref>{{Citation|last=Netmediatama|title=Sarah Sechan - Tahun Baruan bareng Iwan Fals|date=2014-01-01|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KharSea4QO8|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref>\n\nOi was made as the reflection of his passed-away son, and to become the father of his fans.\n\n==Lyrical themes==\nIwan Fals has been compared with Bob Dylan, who was one of his key influences, both on his early style, which made heavy use of the [[harmonica]], and on his lyrics, which have frequently been in the [[protest song]] genre.\n\nFor instance, \"Kamu Sudah Gila\" (\"You've Gone Crazy\") and \"Apa Kamu Sudah Jadi Tuhan?\" (\"Have You Become God?\") criticised the [[New Order (Indonesia)|New Order regime]].\n\nOther songs are more observational, but still could be seen as political. For instance, his song Galang Rambu Anarki, written for his newborn son, talks of being too poor to raise his son, while \"Kembang Pete\" (\"Stinkbean Flower\") tells the story of the underestimated poor.<ref name=\"ginting286\">{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|p=286}}</ref> \"Aku Bosan\" (\"I'm Bored\") is about a child protesting to his parents because they left him alone at home. While \"Hura-Hura Huru-Hara\" (\"Fake Riot\") compares moneylender to blood-sucking vampires.<ref>{{harvnb|Emmerson|1999|p=286}}</ref>\n\nThe 1988 song (and album) '1910', which could be interpreted as referring to the year 1910, was actually a reference to the date 19 October, the date, in 1987, of the [[Bintaro train crash]], a disaster the song documents in observational style. \"Celoteh Camar Tolol dan Cemar\", on 1983's Sumbang, documented the sinking of the ''Tampomas II'' ship in [[Masalembu Islands|Masalembu]].\n\nAside from his observational protest songs, Iwan Fals is known for his love songs, which include \"Yang Terlupakan\" (\"The Forgotten\"), \"Mata Indah Bola Pingpong\" (\"Beautiful Pingpong Ball Eyes\"), \"Antara Kau, Aku, dan Bekas Pacarmu\" (\"Among You, Me, and Your ex-lover\"), and \"Pesawat Tempurku\" (\"My Jet Fighter\").\n\nAlthough a songwriter, Iwan Fals' status as one of Indonesia's leading rock/pop performers has led to his recording material from numerous other songwriters. Some of his most notable hits written by others include Barang Antik (\"Antique\"), \"Kemesraan\" (\"Intimacy\"), \"Kumenanti Seorang Kekasih\" (\"I'm Waiting for a Lover\"), \"Aku Bukan Pilihan\" (\"I'm Not an Option\") and \"Ijinkan Aku Menyayangimu\" (\"Let Me Love You\").<ref>{{harvnb|Ginting|2009|p=289}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 1 January 1982, Fals' first son, Galang Rambu Anarki was born. One of Fals' best-known songs, Galang Rambu Anarki, was written for his son's birth and released on 1982's Opini  (Opinion) album.  Galang was following in his father's footsteps playing in a band from a young age as a guitarist and folk musician, but he died aged only 15, on 25 April 1997 of either a [[morphine]] overdose or asthma. 'Galang Rambu Anarki' translates to \"support the sign of anarchy\" in English.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetmole.org/daily/indonesians-in-focus-iwan-fals.html|title=Indonesians in Focus: Iwan Fals|work=planetmole.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://suaramerdeka.com/v1/index.php/read/cetak/2010/04/22/106730/Dapat-Julukan-Kiai-dari-Santri-Rembang|title=SUARA MERDEKA CETAK - Dapat Julukan Kiai dari Santri Rembang|author=Suara Merdeka CyberNews|work=suaramerdeka.com|access-date=2012-02-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425003809/http://suaramerdeka.com/v1/index.php/read/cetak/2010/04/22/106730/Dapat-Julukan-Kiai-dari-Santri-Rembang|archive-date=2010-04-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Fals' first daughter Annisa Cikal Rambu Basae was born.<ref name=\"ubaedy3\">{{harvnb|Ubaedy|Ratrioso|2005|p=3}}</ref> His third child is Rayya Rambu Robbani.<ref name=\"klc\">{{cite web |url=http://selebriti.kapanlagi.com/indonesia/i/iwan_fals/ |title=Iwan Fals |work=KapanLagi.com |accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref> He and Rosanna, his wife live in [[Cibubur]], [[West Java]].<ref name=\"aning96\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n* Perjalanan (as part of Amburadul group) (1979)\n* Canda Dalam Nada (1979) - comedy album, Iwan has the A-side only\n* Canda Dalam Ronda (1980) - comedy mini-album of four tracks, contains one new track 'Ambulance Zig Zag'\n* 3 Bulan (consists of Perjalanan plus the new track ''3 Bulan'') (1980)\n* [[Sarjana Muda]] (1981) - Musica debut\n* [[Opini]] (1982)\n* [[Sumbang]] (1983)\n* [[Barang Antik]] (1984)\n* [[Sugali (Iwan Fals album)|Sugali]] (1984)\n* [[Kelompok Penyanyi Jalanan]] (KPJ) - as part of KPJ, or Street Singers Group, Iwan Fals sings on 3 songs (1985)\n* [[Sore Tugu Pancoran]] (1985)\n* [[Aku Sayang Kamu]] (1986)\n* [[Ethiopia (Iwan Fals album)|Ethiopia]] (1986)\n* [[Lancar]] (1987)\n* [[Wakil Rakyat]] (1987)\n* 1910 (1988)\n* [[Kemesraan]] (1988) - single, with Betharia Sonata, [[Chrisye]], Rafika Duri, Itang, [[Jamal Mirdad]], Etrie, Nani\n* [[Mata Dewa]] (1989)\n* [[Swami I]] (as part of the group Swami) (1989)\n* [[Kantata Takwa]] (as part of the group Kantata) (1990)\n* [[Cikal]] (1991)\n* [[Swami II]] (as part of the group Swami)  (1991)\n* [[Belum Ada Judul]] (1992)\n* [[Hijau]] (1992)\n* [[Dalbo (Iwan Fals album)|Dalbo]] (1993)\n* [[Anak Wayang]] (1994)\n* [[Orang Gila]] (1994)\n* [[Kantata Samsara]] (as part of the group Kantata) (1998)\n* [[Suara Hati]] (2002)\n* [[In Collaboration with]] (2003)\n* [[Manusia Setengah Dewa]] (2004)\n* [[In Love (Iwan Fals album)|In Love]] (2005) (contains only one new song, and four re-recordings)\n* [[50:50]] (2007)\n* [[Untukmu Terkasih]] (2009) - [[Mini-album]] - two songs only\n* [[Keseimbangan]] (2010)\n* [[Tergila-gila]] (2011)\n* Raya (2013)\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2002, he was named as Great Asian Hero by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"ubaedy4\"/> In 2011, he received \"Satyalancana\", the highest government awards from [[Jero Wacik]], Culture and Tourism Minister of Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/03/24/pop-singer-iwan-fals-receives-highest-government-award-dedication.html |title=Pop singer Iwan Fals receives highest government award for dedication |date=24 March 2011 |newspaper=The Jakarta Post |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013081501/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/03/24/pop-singer-iwan-fals-receives-highest-government-award-dedication.html |archivedate=13 October 2011 |df= }}</ref> \n\nRolling Stone Indonesia listed Swami's song Bongkar as the best Indonesian song of all time and Bento on the fifth position, Kantata Takwa's Kesaksian on 81st position, and Iwan Fals' solo Guru Oemar Bakrie, Yang Terlupakan, Surat Buat Wakil Rakyat, Pesawat Tempur, Galang Rambu Anarki, and Sarjana Muda on 5th, 42nd, 51st, 56th, 65th, and 97th, respectively, making him the second musician with the most representative on the chart after [[Koes Plus]] with the margin of one.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |title=100 Tokoh Yang Mengubah Indonesia |last=Aning S. |first=Floriberta |year=2006 |publisher=Narasi |location=Yogyakarta |isbn=9789797564759 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLrkTdG_9xEC |edition=Revised |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Indonesia Beyond Suharto: Polity, Economy, Society, Transition |last=Emmerson |first=Donald K. |year=1999 |publisher=M. E. Sharpe |location=Armonk, N.Y. |isbn=9781563248900 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQjzLRYXJZQC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Musisiku |last=Ginting |first=Asrat  |year=2009 |publisher=Republika |location=Jakarta |isbn=9789791102520 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ig3oH5TGv4oC |ref=harv|display-authors=etal}}\n* {{cite book |title=Media, Culture and Politics in Indonesia |last=Sen |first=Krishna |last2=Hill |first2=David T. |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=South Melbourne, Vict. |isbn=9780195537031 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xMhWm38KQcsC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Refleksi Kehidupan: Kisah dan Kajian Hidup Orang-Orang Ternama |last=Ubaedy |first=A. N. |first2=Imam |last2=Ratrioso |year=2005 |publisher=Elex Media Komputindo |location=Jakarta |isbn=9789792077254 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o85mshB9IK8C |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fals, Iwan}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Indonesian country singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian songwriters]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Jakarta]]\n", "name_user": "Abdul Salehudin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add new source.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iwan_Fals"}
{"title_page": "Benjamin Levin (partisan)", "text_new": "{{Merge from|Draft:Benjamin Levin (partisan)|date=April 2020}}\n\n''For other people named Benjamin Levin, see [[Benjamin Levin (disambiguation)]]''\n\n'''Benjamin Levin''' (April 11, 1927 \u2013 April 13, 2020) was the last surviving member of the Israeli \u201cAvengers\u201d partisan group. He was responsible for derailing and bombing many Nazi trains. A longstanding warrant for his arrest in Lithuania was still in place seventy years after the war. After the War, he joined the Irgun party, and was one of the surviving passengers of the Altalena ship.\n\n== Early years ==\nLevin was born in [[Vilna, Lithuania]]. He was the son of Chaim Levin, a local merchant and gourmet food shop owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aish.com/ho/p/Jewish-Partisan-Hero-Dies-of-Coronavirus.html|title=Jewish Partisan Hero Dies of Coronavirus|last=Miller|first=Dr Yvette Alt|website=aishcom|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Levin was 14 when he and his older brother joined the \u201cAvengers\u201d (\"Nokmim\") [[partisan group]] of [[Abba Kovner]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/avenger-benjamin-levin-a-young-hero-of-jewish-vilna-succumbs-to-covid-19/|title=\u2018Avenger\u2019 Benjamin Levin, \u2018Forrest Gump of Jewish history,\u2019 succumbs to COVID-19|last=Lebovic|first=Matt|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n== Avengers Partisan Activities ==\nDuring the war, Levin impaired railways, destroyed train cars, cut communication wires, bombed bridges, and injured and killed Nazis. His small stature allowed him to hide, spy, scout, and escape detection easily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/covid-19-defeats-the-last-of-the-partisan-avengers-624850|title=COVID-19 defeats the last of the Partisan Avengers|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nHe and other Avengers joined the Red Army when it liberated Vilnius in 1944.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/benjamin-levin|title=Benjamin Levin|website=encyclopedia.ushmm.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> His parents survived the Holocaust but were later killed with one of their sons by neighbors when they tried to reclaim their home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/18/jewish-nazi-fighter-loses-battle-with-the-coronavirus/|title=Jewish partisan who fought the Nazis loses his battle with coronavirus|last=Vincent|first=Isabel|date=2020-04-18|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Even 70 years after the end of WWII, there was an outstanding warrant for Levin\u2019s arrest in Lithuania. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://206.189.196.188/hera/blog/blog_detail_view/1106?|title=Stuyvesant Blog|website=206.189.196.188|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He submitted his testimony of the Holocaust to the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/vha26425|title=USC Shoah Foundation Institute testimony of Benjamin Levin - Collections Search - United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|website=collections.ushmm.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was interviewed by [[Steven Spielberg]] who dubbed Levin \"the Forrest Gump of Jewish History.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Irgun Party ==\nHe was imprisoned by the [[NKVD]] for illegal resistance activities related to his pre-State Israel activities and involvement in the Irgun party. He spent a year in the Siberian gulag. After his release he hitchhiked to Italy where he rejoined the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishpartisans.org/partisans/benjamin-levin|title=Benjamin Levin|last=Admin|first=Content|date=2016-12-07|website=Jewish Partisan Educational Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He then immigrated to Israel and fled the burning [[Altalena Affair|Altalena]] ship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://israelunwired.com/final-surviving-avenger-nazi-killer-dies-in-ny-from-coronavirus/|title=Final Surviving Nazi-Killer \"Avenger\" Dies in NY from Coronavirus|last=Abelow|first=Avi|date=2020-04-19|website=Israel Unwired|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1967, Levin\u00a0 moved to [[New York City|New York]] with his family and became a mechanic for the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]], a gas-station owner and private business owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2017/04/09/world-war-ii-avenger-reveals-his-heroic-nazi-killing-past/|title=World War II \u2018Avenger\u2019 reveals his heroic Nazi-killing past|last=Vincent|first=Isabel|date=2017-04-09|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was married to Sara, a Hungarian Holocaust survivor. They had two children. Levin died on April 13, 2020 from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc14news.com/2020/04/18/jewish-nazi-fighter-loses-battle-with-the-coronavirus/|title=Jewish Nazi-fighter loses battle with the coronavirus|date=2020-04-18|website=ABC 14 News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish partisans]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Irgun members]]\n[[Category:People from Vilnius]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian Jews]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Merge from|Draft:Benjamin Levin (partisan)|date=April 2020}}\n\n''For other people named Benjamin Levin, see [[Benjamin Levin (disambiguation)]]''\n\n'''Benjamin Levin''' (April 11, 1927 \u2013 April 13, 2020) was the last surviving member of the Israeli \u201cAvengers\u201d partisan group. He was responsible for derailing and bombing many Nazi trains. A longstanding warrant for his arrest in Lithuania was still in place seventy years after the war. After the War, he joined the Irgun party, and was one of the surviving passengers of the Altalena ship.\n\n== Early years ==\nLevin was born in [[Vilna, Lithuania]]. He was the son of Chaim Levin, a local merchant and gourmet food shop owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aish.com/ho/p/Jewish-Partisan-Hero-Dies-of-Coronavirus.html|title=Jewish Partisan Hero Dies of Coronavirus|last=Miller|first=Dr Yvette Alt|website=aishcom|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Levin was 14 when he and his older brother joined the \u201cAvengers\u201d (\"Nokmim\") [[partisan group]] of [[Abba Kovner]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/avenger-benjamin-levin-a-young-hero-of-jewish-vilna-succumbs-to-covid-19/|title=\u2018Avenger\u2019 Benjamin Levin, \u2018Forrest Gump of Jewish history,\u2019 succumbs to COVID-19|last=Lebovic|first=Matt|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\n== Avengers Partisan Activities ==\nDuring the war, Levin impaired railways, destroyed train cars, cut communication wires, bombed bridges, and injured and killed Nazis. His small stature allowed him to hide, spy, scout, and escape detection easily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/israel-news/covid-19-defeats-the-last-of-the-partisan-avengers-624850|title=COVID-19 defeats the last of the Partisan Avengers|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nHe and other Avengers joined the Red Army when it liberated Vilnius in 1944.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/benjamin-levin|title=Benjamin Levin|website=encyclopedia.ushmm.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> His parents survived the Holocaust but were later killed with one of their sons by neighbors when they tried to reclaim their home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/18/jewish-nazi-fighter-loses-battle-with-the-coronavirus/|title=Jewish partisan who fought the Nazis loses his battle with coronavirus|last=Vincent|first=Isabel|date=2020-04-18|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Even 70 years after the end of WWII, there was an outstanding warrant for Levin\u2019s arrest in Lithuania. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://206.189.196.188/hera/blog/blog_detail_view/1106?|title=Stuyvesant Blog|website=206.189.196.188|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He submitted his testimony of the Holocaust to the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.ushmm.org/search/catalog/vha26425|title=USC Shoah Foundation Institute testimony of Benjamin Levin - Collections Search - United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|website=collections.ushmm.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was interviewed by [[Steven Spielberg]] who dubbed Levin \"the Forrest Gump of Jewish History.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Irgun Party ==\nHe was imprisoned by the [[NKVD]] for illegal resistance activities related to his pre-State Israel activities and involvement in the Irgun party. He spent a year in the Siberian gulag. After his release he hitchhiked to Italy where he rejoined the party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishpartisans.org/partisans/benjamin-levin|title=Benjamin Levin|last=Admin|first=Content|date=2016-12-07|website=Jewish Partisan Educational Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He then immigrated to Israel and fled the burning [[Altalena Affair|Altalena]] ship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://israelunwired.com/final-surviving-avenger-nazi-killer-dies-in-ny-from-coronavirus/|title=Final Surviving Nazi-Killer \"Avenger\" Dies in NY from Coronavirus|last=Abelow|first=Avi|date=2020-04-19|website=Israel Unwired|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1967, Levin\u00a0 moved to [[New York]] with his family and became a mechanic for the [[MTA]], a gas-station owner and private business owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2017/04/09/world-war-ii-avenger-reveals-his-heroic-nazi-killing-past/|title=World War II \u2018Avenger\u2019 reveals his heroic Nazi-killing past|last=Vincent|first=Isabel|date=2017-04-09|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was married to Sara, a Hungarian Holocaust survivor. They had two children. Levin died on April 13, 2020 from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc14news.com/2020/04/18/jewish-nazi-fighter-loses-battle-with-the-coronavirus/|title=Jewish Nazi-fighter loses battle with the coronavirus|date=2020-04-18|website=ABC 14 News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jewish partisans]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Irgun members]]\n[[Category:People from Vilnius]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian Jews]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:New York\u2192New York City,MTA\u2192Metropolitan Transportation Authority", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Levin_(partisan)"}
